\begin_layout Standard
Since the interest is in identifying the typical conditions differentiating
 the MIZ from more consolidated and less variable sea ice concentration,
 the median of the indicator computed for each pixel is a useful descriptor
 of the most common spatial features (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sigmaSIA_overview"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 In a Pareto distribution the median is biased towards the lower values,
 hence it is a conservative estimator.
 Higher values of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}$
\end_inset

 median will be indicative of larger departures from the long-term mean
 conditions, when sea ice is present in the region.
 These highly variable regions are found in the outer part of the sea ice
 as expected.
 They are distributed zonally in a homogeneous way, with a few peaks in
 the Bellingshausen, Eastern Weddell Sea (13°E) and Ross Sea (150°W) regions,
 located close to areas of interruptions of the zonal belt.
 Another area of high median is associated to coastal polynyas.
 These are known regions, in which the SIC is recognised to be more variable
 and usually less consolidated.
 A greater halo of variability is observed in the Atlantic sector, extending
 to about 55°S.
 This halo is removed when the analysis is run on the higher level products,
 which are gap-less and/or filtered (supplementary).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The median distribution confirms the presence of different processes underlying
 the variability in Antarctic sea ice that was hinted at when analysing
 the overall distribution in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:PDF-CDF"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}$
\end_inset

 median distribution (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:sigmaSIA_overview"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

b) is more normal and bimodal, also constrained below 0.3 (0.2 is the 99th
 percentile).
 The first peak is larger and centred around 0.05 and the second one is above
 0.15, with a trough between 0.1 and 0.15.
 The change of slope in the empirical CDF is more evident here and correspond
 to the range of values where the two distributions intersect.
 By combining the spatial map with the distribution of the median, it appears
 evident that values between 0.1 and 0.15 indicate mixed regions were consolidated
 pack ice may show concentration changes akin to the features observed at
 the ice margin, and values above 0.15 can be clearly identified as having
 MIZ-like features.
 In the following, I will use a threshold of 0.1 and will discuss the implication
 of this choice.
 Note that this analysis does not differentiate regions of high variation
 based on the distance from the continent, as for instance done in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "stroeveMappingAssessingVariability2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with the SIC threshold criteria.
 MIZ-like conditions can also be found in the interior of the sea ice, as
 it will be shown in the next section.
 The same analysis done on the NOAA/NSIDC GM and OSI-450 data sets shows
 similar features (supplementary), with much cleaner maps at the margin
 with the open ocean.
 However, the filtering introduces a smoothing in the distribution of the
 median.
\end_layout

