\begin_layout Subsection
Exceedance probability of encountering MIZ conditions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Exceedance"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This analysis has indicated that MIZ-like features in Antarctic sea ice
 are not necessarily confined to the outer edge or to coastal polynyas,
 but they can also extend to the interior of the pack ice.
 It is therefore of interest to quantify the likelihood of encountering
 MIZ conditions in a selected month, given the consideration that the SIC
 climatological average is an inadequate descriptor.
 The probability of exceeding a is shown for the threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{SIA}^{m}>0.2$
\end_inset

 in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Exceedance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (0.1 in supplementary).
 It is clear that the SIC variability is different from month to month in
 different sectors of the Southern Ocean.
 This explains why it is difficult to find consistent trends when computing
 hemispheric values.
 For instance, the Ross Sea presents the highest chance to finding variable
 sea-ice state in March over the entire region, while in December this is
 more likely in the Weddell Sea and the Indian sector up to 90°E.
 The regions where the extent of sea ice from the continent is narrower,
 such as Eastern Antarctica, tend to show less variability in the sea-ice
 state.
 In more accurate terms, the probability of exceeding a high value of the
 indicator in East Antarctica sea ice is lower with respect to the other
 regions, but the whole sea-ice covered region should be classified as MIZ,
 since the probability of exceeding the 0.1 threshold is above 80% in every
 month (supplementary).
 This region is therefore one of the most interesting to capture the seasonal
 processes at the air-sea ice-ocean interface, because the MIZ remains at
 the same latitude throughout the year.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, there are lower chances of exceeding the threshold value both
 in the outer edge and in the internal pack ice.
 This feature is caused by two different processes.
 At higher latitudes (mostly in autumn and winter), it is less likely to
 find variable conditions because the sea ice advances so far north only
 in a few years.
 February is an interesting month, because almost in every pixel in which
 sea ice has been observed in the satellite records has a similarly low
 probability to exceed the threshold.
 This means that there are small chances of encountering brash ice but it
 is more likely that open drift conditions will be prevailing.
 June and July are instead the months of higher chances of encountering
 SIC variability away from the edge towards the interior of the Eastern
 Weddell Sea, and hence a sea ice state that is more typical of the MIZ.
\end_layout

